160: Intersection of Two Linked Lists
Problem Statement

Given the heads of two singly linked lists headA and headB, return the node at which the two lists intersect. If the two linked lists have no intersection, return null.

Example
List A: 4 -> 1 \
               8 -> 4 -> 5
List B:    5 -> 6 -> 1 /

Output:

8
Intuition

The two linked lists may have different lengths before they reach the common intersection part.

Instead of calculating lengths separately, we use two pointers:

pA starts from headA
pB starts from headB

When a pointer reaches the end of its list, redirect it to the head of the other list.

This ensures both pointers travel the same total distance:

LengthA + LengthB

As a result:

If an intersection exists, they meet at the intersection node.
If no intersection exists, both pointers become null at the same time.
Approach
Step 1: Initialize Two Pointers
ListNode pA = headA;
ListNode pB = headB;
Step 2: Traverse Until Both Pointers Meet
while (pA != pB)

Continue moving both pointers until they point to the same node.

Step 3: Switch Lists When Reaching the End
pA = (pA == null) ? headB : pA.next;
pB = (pB == null) ? headA : pB.next;
If pA reaches the end of List A, start traversing List B.
If pB reaches the end of List B, start traversing List A.

This equalizes the distance traveled by both pointers.

Step 4: Return the Intersection Node
return pA;

At this point:

pA and pB are either at the intersection node
or both are null
Code
public class Solution {
    public ListNode getIntersectionNode(ListNode headA, ListNode headB) {

        ListNode pA = headA;
        ListNode pB = headB;

        while (pA != pB) {

            pA = (pA == null) ? headB : pA.next;
            pB = (pB == null) ? headA : pB.next;
        }

        return pA;
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
A: 4 -> 1 -> 8 -> 4 -> 5
B: 5 -> 6 -> 1 -> 8 -> 4 -> 5
Initial State
pA = 4
pB = 5
Traversal
pA: 4 -> 1 -> 8 -> 4 -> 5 -> null -> 5 -> 6 -> 1 -> 8
pB: 5 -> 6 -> 1 -> 8 -> 4 -> 5 -> null -> 4 -> 1 -> 8

Eventually:

pA = 8
pB = 8

Both pointers meet at the intersection node.

Return:

8
Why This Works

Suppose:

LengthA = a + c
LengthB = b + c

Where:

a = unique part of List A
b = unique part of List B
c = common intersection part

After switching lists:

Pointer A travels: a + c + b
Pointer B travels: b + c + a

Both pointers travel the same distance, so they align at the intersection node.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(m + n)

Where:

m = length of List A
n = length of List B
Space Complexity
O(1)

No extra data structures are used.

Key Concepts Learned
Two Pointer Technique
pA = (pA == null) ? headB : pA.next;
pB = (pB == null) ? headA : pB.next;

Used to equalize traversal lengths.

Reference Comparison
while (pA != pB)

We compare node references (memory addresses), not node values.

Pattern Learned

Two Pointer Switching Technique

Start pointers at different linked lists.
Traverse normally.
Switch to the other list when reaching the end.
Meet at the intersection node.

This pattern is useful in problems involving:

Linked list intersections
Equalizing path lengths
Pointer synchronization
Takeaway

The optimal solution avoids computing lengths explicitly. By allowing each pointer to traverse both linked lists, both pointers travel the same total distance and naturally meet at the intersection node.

Time Complexity: O(m + n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

